  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To strengthen this threat, Amos proceeds, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 9:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 9:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to describe Jehovah as the Lord of heaven and earth, who sends judgments upon the earth with omnipotent power. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 9:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"And the Lord Jehovah of hosts, who toucheth the earth, and it melteth, and all the inhabitants of thereupon mourn; and the whole of it riseth like the Nile, and sinketh like the Nile of Egypt. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 9:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Who buildeth His stories in heaven, and His vault, over the earth hath He founded it; who calleth to the waters of the sea, and poureth them out over the earth: Jehovah is His name.\" This description of God, who rules with omnipotence, is appended, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 4:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 5:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", without any link of connection whatever. We must not render it, \"The Lord Jehovah of hosts is He who toucheth the earth;\" but we must supply the connecting thought, \"And He who thus directeth His eye upon you is the Lord Jehovah of hosts, who toucheth the earth, and it melteth.\" The melting or dissolving of the earth is, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 46:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", an effect produced by the Lord, who makes His voice heard in judgments, or \"the destructive effect of the judgments of God, whose instruments the conquerors are\" (Hengstenberg), when nations reel and kingdoms totter. The Lord therefore touches the earth, so that it melts, when He dissolves the stability of the earth by great judgments (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 75:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"Israel could not fail to test the truth of these words by painful experience, when the wild hordes of Assyria poured themselves over the western parts of Asia\" (Hengstenberg). The following words, depicting the dissolution of the earth, are repeated, with very inconsiderable alterations, from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 8:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; we have merely the omission of ונגרשׁה, and the kal שׁקעה substituted for the niphal נשׁקה. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 9:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " there is evidently an allusion to the flood. God, who is enthroned in heaven, in the cloud-towers built above the circle of the earth, possesses the power to pour the waves of the sea over the earth by His simple word. Ma‛ălōth is synonymous with עליּות in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 104:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : upper rooms, lit., places to which one has to ascend. 'Aguddâh, an arch or vault: that which is called râqı̄ă‛, the firmament, in other places. The heaven, in which God builds His stories, is the heaven of clouds; and the vault, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 1:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is the firmament of heaven, which divided the water above the firmament from the water beneath it. Consequently the upper rooms of God are the waters above the firmament, in or out of which God builds His stories (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 104:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), i.e., the cloud-tower above the horizon of the earth, which is raised above it like a vault. Out of this cloud-castle the rain pours down (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 104:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and out of its open windows the waters of the flood poured down, and overflowed the earth (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 7:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). When God calls to the waters of the sea, they pour themselves over the surface of the earth. The waves of the sea are a figurative representation of the agitated multitude of nations, or of the powers of the world, which pour their waves over the kingdom of God (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 7:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]